Here's a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    // Open the input file
    std::ifstream inputFile("input.txt");

    // Check if the file was opened successfully
    if (!inputFile) {
        std::cerr << "Error: Unable to open input file!\n";
        return -1;
    }

    // Initialize the word to search for and the count variable
    std::string searchWord = "the";
    int wordCount = 0;

    // Read the file line by line
    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(inputFile, line)) {
        // Search for the word in the current line
        size_t pos = line.find(searchWord);
        while (pos != std::string::npos) {
            // Increment the count variable and continue searching
            wordCount++;
            pos = line.find(searchWord, pos + 1);
        }
    }

    // Close the input file
    inputFile.close();

    // Print the results
    std::cout << "The word \"" << searchWord << "\" appears " << wordCount << " times in the file.\n";

    return 0;
}
```

This program first opens an input file named "input.txt" and checks if the file was opened successfully. It then initializes the word to search for and the count variable to 0.

The program then reads the file line by line using the `std::getline()` function and searches for the word in each line using the ` std::string::find()` function. If the word is found in the line, the count variable is incremented and the program continues searching for the word in the rest of the line.

After all lines have been read and searched, the input file is closed and the program prints the number of occurrences of the word in the file.

Note: This program assumes that the input file contains only text and not binary data. If the input file contains binary data, this program will not work correctly.

